AGI - March 2024 was warmer globally than any previous March recorded in data, with an average temperature of the ERA5 surface air of 14.14 centigrade degrees, about 0.73 above the average period 1991-2020 for March and 0.10 above the previous maximum established in March 2016. It was the tenth hottest consecutive month ever recorded for its fraction of the year. These are the data collected by the Copernicus Climate Change (C3S) service, implemented by the European Centre for Medium-Term Weather Forecasts on behalf of the European Commission with EU funding. The month was 1.68 degrees warmer than an average March estimate for the period 1850-1900, the designated preindustrial reference period. The global average temperature of the last twelve months (April 2023 - March 2024) is the highest ever recorded, equal to 0,70 degrees Celsius over the average period 1991-2020 and 1,58 over the preindustrial average of the period 1850-1900.
&nbsp;
The average European temperature for March 2024 was 2.12 degrees higher than the average of March 1991-2020, making the month the second of March warmest ever recorded for the continent, only slightly cooler - than just 0.02 degrees - compared to March 2014. Temperatures were higher than average in central and eastern regions. Outside Europe, temperatures were higher than average in Eastern North America, Greenland, Eastern Russia, Central America, parts of South America, many parts of Africa, South Australia and parts of Antarctica. El Nino continued to weaken in the eastern equatorial Pacific, but sea air temperatures in general remained at an unusually high level.&nbsp; The global average temperature of the sea surface for March between 60 degrees of South longitude and 60 degrees North was 21,07 degrees Celsius, the highest monthly value ever recorded, slightly higher than 21,06 degrees Celsius recorded for February.
&nbsp;
Samantha Burgess, Deputy Director of the Copernicus Climate Service (C3S), stressed the importance of the situation: "March 2024 continues the sequence of climate records in decline both for air temperature and ocean surface temperature, with the tenth consecutive record month. The global average temperature is the highest ever recorded, with 1.58 degrees above pre-industrial levels in the last 12 months. To stop further heating it is necessary to quickly reduce greenhouse gas emissions".
&nbsp;
The Arctic marine ice extension reached its annual maximum in March, with a monthly value slightly lower than average, marking the highest extension of March since 2013. As in January and February, the anomalies of the concentration of marine ice were mixed throughout the Arctic Ocean. The concentrations remained above the average in the Greenland Sea, a persistent feature since October. The antarctic sea ice extension was 20% lower than average, the sixth lowest extension of March in the satellite data record, continuing a series of major negative abnormalities observed since 2017. As in February, sea ice concentrations were lower than average in the North Weddell Sea and the Ross-Amundsen Sea.
&nbsp;
In March 2024 the climate was damper than average in most Western Europe, with storms that caused heavy rain on the Iberian Peninsula and southern France. The climate has been more humid than the average even in the regions of Scandinavia and northwestern Russia. The rest of Europe was mainly drier than the average, with precipitations much lower than the average on northwestern Norway. In March 2024, the climate was damper than average in North America, all over Central Asia, Japan, most of the Arabian Peninsula, Madagascar and some parts of South America. Australia lived an exceptionally rainy month. More dry conditions than the average have been established in some parts of the central United States, western Canada and northern Mexico, regions of Central Asia and China and southeastern Australia, most of southern Africa and South America.

